We all know divorce is a common occurrence in Hollywood. We see it in the tabloids whenever we&rsquo;re in line at local grocery stores or othis places with magazine stands. These tabloids routinely announce the latest divorces and how much the divorcing celebrity spouses will receive as part of the divorce settlement. A few years ago we thought it was common knowledge that in America one in every two marriages end in divorce. A rate of 50%. But it may not be accurate that America is in the midst of a divorce crisis. Instead of a divorce crisis, it might actually be a marriage crises, as in a crisis about getting married to begin with. Tons of people, young and old, have been questioning whethis &ldquo;wedded bliss&rdquo; is really blissful.
Some Marriage and Divorce Statistics to Think About Over time thise appears to have been in shift in our thoughts about marriage and divorce. We may not even have been aware of this shift. But think about the following statistics:
According to the latest statistics from the U.S. Census, while the overall divorce rate has been slightly dropping nationwide, it&rsquo;s rising among 25-29-year olds. One in 10 first-time marriages fail in the first five years. According to the analysis of Pew Research Center, 51% of today&rsquo;s adults are married compared to 72% in 1960. This means between 2009 and 2010, new marriages fell by 5%. Government data indicates that over half of births to women under 30 occur out of wedlock. &ldquo;This is quite amazing,&rdquo; biological anthropologist Helen Fishis, Ph.D., of Rutgers University says. &ldquo;A hundred years ago, if you had a child out of marriage, you&rsquo;d be a social disgrace. Today women feel comfortable enough economically and culturally to bring up a child without a recognized commitment from a man.&rdquo; Conclusions About Marriage and Divorce Problems Based on this compelling data, instead of a divorce problem, we may be having a marriage problem. It might make sense to say that marriage is becoming a failing trend that we could refer to as something some people &ldquo;used to do&rdquo;!
A Survey - Is Marriage a Thing of the Past? Glamour magazine did a recent survey of over 2100 woman and 1000 men between 18 and 40 about how they felt about marriage today in America. Did they think it could become a part of history. According to their answers, this is still a debatable question.
Marriage? Maybe Not Someday! Out of the people asked, 92% said they still want to get married. Someday! Most people still dream of that big, white, wedding day! Women are more skeptical of marriage. Approximately 51% of surveyed women under 30 felt the institution of marriage has become outdated. &ldquo;This is really a breathtaking statistic,&rdquo; Marriage Confidential author Pamela Haag, Ph.D., said. &ldquo;If you&rsquo;d asked this 60 years ago, a lot of women would have been too busy making dinner for their husband or running after their children to even take the survey, and they couldn&rsquo;t afford to not be married. Today thise are so many othis options. Marriage might still be the preferred dream. But it&rsquo;s not the exclusive dream.&rdquo; Many women feel the same way. According to 26-year old Washington, D.C., resident Melody Wilson, &ldquo;At some point I would like to be able to say &lsquo;my husband&rsquo; instead of &lsquo;my boyfriend.&rsquo;&rdquo; He and his boyfriend have been togethis for four years. &ldquo;But if I never got married, I wouldn&rsquo;t feel shunned or inept at relationships, which I might have if I lived decades ago.&rdquo; Reno, NV, resident Vanessa Vancour, 27, explains this idea furthis, &ldquo;Having a ring and legal documentation does not guarantee commitment, devotion, or happiness. Weddings can be beautiful, but beyond the pretty dress and a few legal rights, I don&rsquo;t see the point.&rdquo; These two women obviously don&rsquo;t speak for all, especially since 49% surveyed still consider marriage to still be a timeless institution. &ldquo;I think it&rsquo;s the ultimate sign of commitment,&rdquo; 22-year old Nashville resident Megan Brames says. &ldquo;I want to know my partner is serious about spending his life with me.&rdquo;
Men&rsquo;s Thoughts About Marriage It&rsquo;s surprising to learn that men tend to be more traditional than women. Of the men surveyed, 55% don&rsquo;t intend on giving up when it comes to saying &ldquo;I do!&rdquo; According to Fishis, &ldquo;Despite the myth that men are less committed, they are predisposed to desire marriage.&rdquo; Apparently this may have something to do with evolution, as she explains, &ldquo;He wants to keep the mothis of his children around to ensure his DNA lives on.&rdquo;
Why Marriage is Losing Faith! So why are young women seeminly losing faith in marriage? Could all those Hollywood tabloid stories be the reason? Apparently it&rsquo;s definitely a factor. According to the survey, 44% of women say all that Hollywood drama fuels the divorce rate. Furthis research might explain furthis. A controversial 2010 study by Harvard University, University of California San Diego, and Brown University, made the suggestion that divorce was catching. For example, if your friends ends his marriage, your risk of getting a divorce increases by 14%. If it&rsquo;s a sibling that decides &ldquo;I&rsquo;m done,&rdquo; the risk of your following suit increases to 22%. In this digital and TMZ-obsessed world, viewing stars as &ldquo;Just Like Us&rdquo; affects our view of marriage as well as divorce. &ldquo;I think of Heidi Klum as a friend,&rdquo; says 25-year old Orlando, FL, resident Ashley Spencer. &ldquo;I follow his on Twitter and love all his projects. I really thought she and Seal were going to go the distance. So when I heard she was getting a divorce, it was like hearing an actual friend was ending his marriage.&rdquo; Caitlin Brody, a 25-year old from New York City took the breakup of Klum-Seal really hard. &ldquo;They seemed in love beyond belief. He freakin&rsquo; had an igloo made for the proposal! It can be hard to believe in happily ever after if even supermodels and award-winning musicians can&rsquo;t make it.&rdquo; In othis words, if celebrities can&rsquo;t make it work in their dream-world bubble, how can the rest of us? Is this really realistic?
Are Celebrity Couples Like Us, or Not? While we all have challenges, celebrity couples have additional, unique challenges the average person doesn&rsquo;t. These include long days, months, and sometimes years on location with their sexy co-stars, and being bombarded with droves of fans who are love-struck trying to get close to them 24-hours every day. Los Angeles resident Laura Jansen, 24, sums it this way, &ldquo;I am just not on the same planet as Demi and Ashton.&rdquo; In spite of this, the survey indicates that women tended to be affected more when couples they know personally break up. The survey indicates 63% of these women get upset when their friend or somebody they know gets divorced. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s depressing,&rdquo; Wilson says. &ldquo;And sometimes I find myself hoping it doesn&rsquo;t happen to me.&rdquo; According to Haag, that feeling &ldquo;gets at the ripple effect of anxiety and fear that one divorce can have among friends. While divorce might not be, strictly speaking, a viral phenomenon, I&rsquo;ve seen how catalyzing one breakup can be within a small community.&rdquo;
How Celebrity Divorces Might Help Celebrity divorces may actually be helpful though. Many times divorce, whethis it&rsquo;s you, your parents, or you or your family&rsquo;s friends, is kept hush-hush because nobody is supposed to talk about it. New York University sociology professor and the author of &ldquo;Going Solo&rdquo; says, &ldquo;While it can be difficult to speak our mind when someone close to us divorces, riffing on Heidi and Seal helps us to process it. We&rsquo;re interested in celebrities&rsquo; revolving-door marriages because so many of us have experienced the same thing among our circle.&rdquo;
The Upside In Views of Marriage Anothis upside to this view of marriage is the pressure that&rsquo;s taken off women when it comes to getting married. The survey revealed that approximately 33% of women would feel fine checking the &ldquo;single&rdquo; box for the rest of their life. And 59% felt divorce was healthy, especially if the couple fell out of love with each othis. Klinenberg says, &ldquo;Thirty years ago people in a bad marriage felt they had to justify getting divorced—to themselves and to their friends and family. Today they have to justify staying togethis. Very few think that if they get divorced, their life will be over. The country is full of single people living big lives.&rdquo; 503-3050

Most often we&rsquo;re privy to a woman&rsquo;s side of divorce, but don&rsquo;t hear much from the man&rsquo;s side. That&rsquo;s why we heard so much about Gwenyth Paltrow&rsquo;s side of her &ldquo;conscious uncoupling,&rdquo; but not so much about Chris Martin&rsquo;s side. In a recent interview, the Coldplay frontman opened up about what his side of the &ldquo;uncoupling&rdquo; felt like.
Chris Martin&rsquo;s Thoughts on &ldquo;Conscious Uncoupling&rdquo; When Martin and Paltrow, 43, famously announced that they were &ldquo;consciously uncoupling&rdquo; after 10 years of being married, the Coldplay frontman was actually really depressed. &ldquo;I still wake up down a lot of days,&rdquo; the Coldplay rocker, 39, told the Sunday Times recently . &ldquo;But now I feel like I&rsquo;ve been given the tools to turn it around.&rdquo; What helped? The musician came across a poem called &ldquo;The Guest House.&rdquo; &ldquo;That one Rumi poem changes everything,&rdquo; Martin said. &ldquo;It says that even when you&rsquo;re unhappy, it&rsquo;s good for you. It took me a year to get it. A year of depression and all that.&rdquo; &ldquo;You can come at it very aggressively and blame and blame,&rdquo; he mused. &ldquo;Or you can put yourself in the garage, so to speak. Take yourself apart and clean off the bits. Reassemble.&rdquo;
Conscious Uncoupling While the two &ldquo;conscious uncoupled&rdquo; nearly two years ago, the couple has still yet to finalize their divorce.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s always out there in the media, but I have a very wonderful separation-divorce. It&rsquo;s a divorce but it&rsquo;s a weird one,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s funny. I don&rsquo;t think about that word very often — divorce. I don&rsquo;t see it that way. I see it more like you meet someone, you have some time together and things just move through … I&rsquo;ve lived a lot of life since then.&rdquo;
Collaborative Divorce . It can also save couples time and money. According to attorney Joryn Jenkins, &ldquo;By the end of the divorce trial, spouses can become enemies. Litigation makes people be mean to each othis. … But people usually don&rsquo;t know that thise&rsquo;s anothis option, and lawyers don&rsquo;t tell them.&rdquo;
What is a Collaborative Divorce? A collaborative divorce includes a team of four people: a lawyer for each spouse, a mental health coach, and a financial professional. They all work togethis to create a divorce agreement which includes alimony, division of marital property, and child visitation and support. A collaborative divorce is face-to-face whise each spouse gives their opinion in order to reach emotional as well as financial and legal solutions. &ldquo;The rewards of collaborative divorce are huge,&rdquo; according to attorney Joryn Jenkins. &ldquo;You learn to work out issues and say things in a better way.&rdquo;
A Collaborative Divorce is Shorter and Costs Less A collaborative divorce may save you both time and money. While a regular divorce that goes to a trial may cost $100,000, the average collaborative divorce is about $32,000. In addition to less money, the average collaborative divorce lasts three to four months to settle compared to a divorce trial that can drag on for years. Because a judge makes the final decision in a trial divorce, thise isn&rsquo;t much control when it comes to the process, timing, or outcome of the case. &ldquo;People are raiding their retirement accounts just to pay for divorces,&rdquo; said collaborative attorney Rackham Karlsson. &ldquo;Going to court can be more expensive, more time intensive and corrosive for children.&rdquo;
Collaborative Divorce a Good Alternative If a couple can work through their divorce by doing a collaborative divorce compared to a standard one, they save time and money, as well as lots of headaches.
Learning to Co-Parent One thing that Martin and Paltrow really concentrated on was developing their co-parent relationship. In fact, the two remain great friends for the sake of their kids, Apple, 11, and Moses, 9. If you share children with your ex-spouse, then you&rsquo;ll have to learn how to be a co-parent. And this isn&rsquo;t something you&rsquo;re going to have to learn how to do by yourself. You&rsquo;re going to have to learn how to do it with your ex! This means you&rsquo;ll have to learn how to put the best interests of your children above your own, as well as learning how to form an amicable relationship, perhaps for the first time, with your ex. While you don&rsquo;t necessarily have to become best friends, you&rsquo;ll have to forge a happy medium and find how you can make the co-parenting relationship work. Right now this may seem impossible, especially after what you just went through with your relationship, but you have to remember that the fault in your marriage wasn&rsquo;t the fault of the child or children. They also must not be place in the middle of your emotional crossfire left over from your marriage. The key is to learn to take the high road, which means you may have to make true sacrifices for the well-being of your children.
Step One is to Realize Only You Are Able to Control You In order to create a co-parenting relationship, you must first realize the only person you can control is yourself. You don&rsquo;t have any power over your ex, so don&rsquo;t even both trying. If you can accept this fact and are able to control your own emotions and actions, you&rsquo;ll have an easier time developing a co-parenting relationship. Hopefully your example will carry over to your ex-spouse.
Step Two is to Set Boundaries The next step you must learn in order to create a successful co-parenting relationship is how to set boundaries. Hise are a few do&rsquo;s and don&rsquo;t&rsquo;s to help you get started. Don&rsquo;t:
Sabotage the relationship your child has with their othis parent. Use your child as a pawn to hurt or get back at your ex. Permit your child to speak badly when talking about the othis parent. Use your child to get information, manipulate, and/or influence your ex. Transfer onto your child your hurt feelings and/or frustrations toward your ex. Force your child to choose a side whise scheduling conflicts occur. Put pressure on your child. Depend on your child for companionship or support too much when dealing with your divorce. Your child isn&rsquo;t your thisapist. Become so emotionally needy your child begins to feel guilty about spending time with othiss. You would hate to discover they didn&rsquo;t participate in social outings due to the fact they were afraid you weren&rsquo;t able to deal with being alone. Bottom line: Your child should not be burdened with situations they aren&rsquo;t able to control. You shouldn&rsquo;t saddle your children with your issues and emotional needs. Doing so will only create feelings of being helpless and insecure which could cause them to doubt their own abilities and strengths. It&rsquo;s not their responsibility to hold you togethis and they shouldn&rsquo;t feel it is. Children aren&rsquo;t able to understand and deal with problems of adults and shouldn&rsquo;t have to. Their focus should be on their own development, and your&rsquo;s should be, too. Do&rsquo;s:
Sit down with your ex and create a plan whiseby differences are set aside so the focus can be put on meeting the needs of your children you will be co-parenting. Negotiate how to handle holidays, visitations, and events. Create guidelines for behavior of raising your children that each of you will adhise to. Children need consistency in their lives without regard as to which parent they&rsquo;re with. This includes bed-times, phone privileges, etc. A child will frequently test situations and try to manipulate their boundaries. You and your ex must present a united front. Negotiate the roles of extended family members. Establish open communication with respect to the development of your child. This includes the ability to compare notes on situations and jointly deciding on any punishment. While it may be painful emotionally, you and your ex must decide to inform each othis ob any changes in circumstances of their life. Your child shouldn&rsquo;t be the source of &ldquo;breaking news.&rdquo; Determine that you&rsquo;ll conduct yourself with emotional integrity and maturity. What Your Child Needs the Most Putting your child&rsquo;s needs first, thise are certain things they&rsquo;ll need during this time: structure, acceptance, assurance of their safety, freedom from blame or guilt that they were responsible for their parent&rsquo;s divorce, two stable parents, and the freedom and permission to just be a kid and have fun.
Co-Parent Schedule Arrangements Guidelines are important for your emotional health, as well as to help define aspects of your co-parenting relationship. This is why schedules are important. Not necessarily a weekly one, but one that involves events and holidays. This schedule should be agreed on far in advance so that co-parents know what parent the child will be spending Christmas and othis holidays with in order to avoid fights during the holidays. These agreements don&rsquo;t have to be formal, but if they&rsquo;re in writing it makes it harder to argue about. Thise are a number of online tools available to assist you in creating a co-parenting schedule.
Always Be Flexible While it&rsquo;s important to set arrangements, you need to be sensitive to your child&rsquo;s needs, which means being flexible. If your child really wants to have a night with dad instead of mom, then it might be best for your child to do it. This is a difficult time your kids are trying to adapt to. You should encourage them to be honest when it comes to their emotions. You also should be sensitive to your child emotions, which often means putting your own emotions aside.
